{{Orphan|date=September 2018}}

A '''ceramic valve''' is a [[valve]] with [[ceramic]] trim, ball, seat, disc or lining.  A carbon or stainless steel body is used to protect the ceramic trim from being damaged by sudden thermal or mechanical shock. Advanced ceramics are used in the manufacture including [[alumina]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azom.com/article.aspx?ArticleID=11082|title=Zirconia – Properties and Applications by Precision Ceramics|accessdate=2014-07-14|publisher=azom.com}}</ref> [[zirconia]] and [[silicon nitride]]. Significant benefits of the use of ceramic in valves (when compared to steel or other traditional materials) include resistance to wear and their lower mass.<ref>{{cite journal|title=15th Annual Conference on Composites and Advanced Ceramic |number=9|page=1935|author=John B. Wachtman|year=1991}}</ref> Thanks to the excellent corrosion resistance, abrasive  resistance and wear resistance, ceramic valves are often used in severe corrosive and abrasive applications, such as [[Flue-gas desulfurization|FGD]], and [[pneumatic refuse conveying system]]s.

