'''Revolution Money''' is a [[financial services]] company based in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]].<ref>https://www.revolutioncard.com/WebSite/about_us.aspx{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The company's products include a PIN based [[credit card]], online person to person payments service, with a linked stored value card, and gift card. Revolution Money is the only credit card that does not charge retailers [[interchange fee]]s.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Clark|first1=Emily|title=Revolution Money offers online payment alternative|url=http://newatlas.com/go/8124/|website=Newatlas.com|accessdate=16 January 2017}}</ref> The company partnered with [[Yahoo! Sports]] and [[Fifth Third Bank]].

Revolution Money has three products: RevolutionCard is a credit card, Revolution MoneyExchange which provides free online money transfers between members, and RevolutionGift, the gift card. Revolution MoneyExchange accounts are issued by [[First Bank and Trust]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Manning|first1=Margie|title=St. Petersburg credit card company launches a Revolution|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/tampabay/stories/2007/08/20/story7.html|website=Bizjournals.com|accessdate=16 January 2017}}</ref>

== Background ==
Revolution MoneyExchange was an online bank intended as an alternative to [[PayPal]] and its chief competitor, [[Google Checkout]]. It was founded as GratisCard in April 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://geek-news.net/2008/02/revolution-money-exchange.html|work=Geek-News.Net|title=Revolution Money Exchange|date=2008-02-10|accessdate=2008-07-15}}</ref> [[Ted Leonsis]] and [[Steve Case]] were on its board of directors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ted.aol.com/category.php?catID=650|work=Ted's Take|title=Small Correction|date=2008-02-11|accessdate=2008-07-15|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707151432/http://ted.aol.com/category.php?catID=650|archivedate=2011-07-07|df=}}</ref> Revolution MoneyExchange was backed by [[Citi]], [[Morgan Stanley]], and [[Deutsche Bank AG]], as well as its parent company, Revolution LLC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mymoneyblog.com/archives/2008/01/revolution-moneyexchange-new-person-to-person-payment-system-and-25-bonus-promotion.html|work=MyMoneyBlog|title=Revolution MoneyExchange: New Person-to-Person Payment System and $25 Bonus Promotion|date=2008-01-31|accessdate=2008-07-15}}</ref>

There were no fees charged for online transfers between accounts. The Revolution MoneyExchange Card was a [[stored-value card]] that allowed account holders to access their funds for purchases at merchant locations on the RevolutionCard network and for cash withdrawals at [[automated teller machine|ATM]]s nationwide.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Graham|first1=Jefferson|title=Talkin' 'bout a Revolution in transferring money online|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/tech/techinvestor/corporatenews/2007-11-06-ted-leonis-steve-case_N.htm|website=Usatoday.com|accessdate=16 January 2017}}</ref>

RevolutionGift is a prepaid PIN based [[gift card]] with no account number printed on the card. Other features included the capacity to send money via [[AOL Instant Messenger]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.revolutionmoney.com/PressUpdates/YouveGotPayments-AOLFounderBacksP-to-PStart-Up.pdf|work=American Banker|title=You've Got Payments - AOL Founder Backs P-to-P Start-Up|date=2007-09-25|accessdate=2008-07-15}}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> <!--RevolutionMoneyExchange is hosting the article as press coverage; however, the source is well identified as American Banker, so it is American Banker's work. Additionally, there is a paywall to American Banker articles. http://www.americanbanker.com/issues/172_189/-330859-1.html -->

On November 18, 2009, [[American Express]] announced that it would acquire Revolution Money for US$500 million, and finally did for US$300 million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/American-Express-to-buy-apf-2466608827.html?x=0&sec=topStories&pos=2&asset=&ccode= |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-01-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091122093514/http://finance.yahoo.com/news/American-Express-to-buy-apf-2466608827.html?x=0&sec=topStories&pos=2&asset=&ccode= |archive-date=2009-11-22 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> Revolution MoneyExchange was purchased by American Express in January 2010, and was renamed Serve Virtual Enterprises, Inc. Serve Enterprises then launched Serve and discontinued Revolution MoneyExchange on March 28, 2011.

